body: Can one of the admins verify this patch?

Yes, that's what I intended.

The first except is there in case stdout is not an int, in which case we should tell the user explicitly that there is interference from some other output, so they can deal with it before trying again (e.g. in your case, they are prompted to build an assembly jar). The alternative of surfacing an obscure ValueError is much more confusing.

The second except is there for all other exceptions that could happen (e.g. if we fail to read from process output for some reason). This doesn't add much information other than the exit code (if there is one).

But in the case I posted, it's not that stdout is interfering; the stdout is descriptive of an error that should be fixed.  Also now we lose other lines of the error message (in the case I posted, a second line says "You need to build Spark before running this program") which can be helpful / necessary for debugging.
Ah I see, currently we only return 1 line of the output, when we should really return all of it.
for computeSVD and computeSparseSVD with two parameters k and computeU. I still keep the default for computeU. Removing the default value breaks some other classes...
Good catch. I have also removed the second except because I realize it actually masks the original stack trace in exchange for information that is not super useful.
